{'text': 'It is possible that decriminalization dissuades those who specifically start using drugs as a way of breaking the law, such as [early data from Portugal](https://www.leafly.com/news/politics/portugal-drug-decriminalization-statistics) suggests.'}
{'text': "Without effective law enforcement, legalizing drugs might fuel criminal gang's economies (e.g., illegal trade)."}

{'text': 'Drug prohibition might be inspired by some kind of racism but abandoning it would not necessarily mean an improvement of the situation for those incarcerated or addicted to drugs. There are still many other systematic racial issues unrelated to drug prohibition.'}

Marijuana is one of the least damaging mind altering substances and yet, is still federally illegal (in the US).'}
{'text': 'It is better to educate people on how to use valuable-yet-dangerous things safely than to ban their use entirely.'}

{'text': "As this is also true under prohibition, it's an argument for proper education, not an argument against legalization."}

{'text': 'Laws should be introduced on an entirely pragmatic basis, not on the basis of moral signaling. If legalising drugs reduces harm, this should be sufficient evidence that it is a good policy.'}

{'text': 'The existing drug classification systems is arbitrary and has little relation to any evidence of the harmfulness of the drugs in question. [(Nutt DJ et al. 2010)](http://www.ias.org.uk/uploads/pdf/News%20stories/dnutt-lancet-011110.pdf)'}
